SIMPLE: hither
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hither
<hw>Hith"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>hider</ets>, AS. <ets>hider</ets>; akin to Icel.
<ets>h⟦emac⟧⟦edh⟧ra</ets>, Dan. <ets>hid</ets>, Sw. <ets>hit</ets>,
Goth. <ets>hidr⟦emac⟧</ets>; cf. L. <ets>citra</ets> on this side, or E.
<ets>here</ets>, <ets>he</ets>. ⟦root⟧183. Cf. <er>He</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To this place; -- used with verbs signifying motion,
and implying motion toward the speaker; correlate of <xex>hence</xex>
and <xex>thither</xex>; <as>as, to come or bring
<ex>hither</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To this point, source, conclusion, design, etc.; --
in a sense not physical.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Hither</qex> we refer whatsoever belongeth unto the highest
perfection of man.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Hither and thither</b></col>, <cd>to and fro; backward
and forward; in various directions.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Victory is like a
traveller, and goeth <xex>hither and thither</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Knolles.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hither</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hither
<hw>Hith"er</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Being on the side next
or toward the person speaking; nearer; -- correlate of
<xex>thither</xex> and <xex>farther</xex>; <as>as, on the
<ex>hither</ex> side of a hill</as>.</def> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Applied to time: On the hither side of, younger
than; of fewer years than.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And on the <qex>hither</qex> side, or so she looked,⟦br⟧
Of twenty summers.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To the present generation, that is to say, the people a few years
on the <qex>hither</qex> and thither side of thirty, the name of
<person>Charles Darwin</person> stands alongside of those of
<person>Isaac Newton</person> and <person>Michael Faraday</person>.</q>
<rj><qau>Huxley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hithermost</ent>⟦br⟧
